<h2>My personal site</h2>

<p>I recently undertook a refresh of the design of my personal website and blog and occasionally I get asked (mainly by other developers, never usually clients) if I've spent much time catering for legacy browsers and if not, why not. </p>
<p>I started developing <em>on the edge</em> recently - using {{link "[Chrome Canary](https://www.google.co.uk/intl/en/chrome/browser/canary.html)"}} and testing in {{link "[Firefox Nightly](http://nightly.mozilla.org)"}}, just cos I love playing with new features as they're implemented. And also Nightly's UI just looks stunning at the moment, I have to say.</p>
<p>Although I like to take advantage of being able to develop in the newest browsers with the latest implementations of features and standards I still think about backwards compatibility and graceful degradation throughout the development process, as well as testing in legacy browsers where needed.</p>

<h2>Who really cares?</h2>

<p><em>We do.</em></p>
<p>So I've been thinking and it's an interesting idea that it's never clients or users who actually realise that your website or webapp may be different or gracefully degrading in older browsers, always us who notice the quirks and differences between how they look or function.</p>
<p>We as developers are sometime still clinging to this idea that we should achieve cross browser perfection, that all websites should look exactly the same in every browser, IE7-11 and all modern browsers included. Hint: {{link "[its ok if](http://dowebsitesneedtolookexactlythesameineverybrowser.com)"}} {{link "[they don't](http://dowebsitesneedtobeexperiencedexactlythesameineverybrowser.com/)"}}.</p>
